            <div type="translation" resp="part:emfr">
                
                <p n="1-22">
                    In the fifth year of Parākrama Bahu Niccaṅka<note>That is, Niśśaṅka.</note> Mallaṉ, king of Southern Laṅkā,
                    at the time of an auspiscious conjunction <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>naṟ-cāta-yōkattil?</foreign></supplied>, on the day of Jupiter <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>poṉṉavaṉ tiṉam</foreign><note>That is, Thursday.</note></supplied>, seven<supplied reason="subaudible">th day in</supplied> the fortnight <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>y-ēḻ pakkam</foreign>?<note>We follow here existing translations, but this expression is not usual.</note></supplied>, <supplied reason="subaudible">with the <foreign>nakṣatra</foreign></supplied> Uttiraṭṭāti, in <supplied reason="subaudible">the month of</supplied> Tai <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>v-it-taiyyil?</foreign></supplied> when the sun joins in the Capricorn <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>tiṉakaraṉ cuṟavil aṇainta</foreign></supplied>,
                    
                    for the excellent enlightened ascetic <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>pōti-mātavaṟku</foreign></supplied>,<note>That is, the Buddha, as <foreign>pōti</foreign> is Sanskrit <foreign>bodhi</foreign>.</note>
                    <supplied reason="subaudible">in his</supplied> beautiful <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>poṟp' amar
</foreign></supplied> temple,
                    
                    
                    the fighter <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>kaṇṭaṉ</foreign></supplied> of the five <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>aivar</foreign><note>That is, the Pāṇḍyas?</note></supplied>,
                    <gap reason="ellipsis"/>
                    
                    established <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>amaittāṉ</foreign></supplied> with joy <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>makiḻntēy</foreign></supplied>
                    in Śrīpuranakar
                    a residence for the ascetics, 
                    a feeding hall <gap reason="ellipsis"/>,
                    and a <foreign>caitya</foreign> <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>cayittam</foreign></supplied>.
                </p>
            </div>
            
            <div type="translation" source="bib:KanapathiPillai1960_02">                
                <p n="1-22">
                    In the fifth year of Parākramabāhu Niccaṅka Mallar, the king of South Ceylon, on the occasion of the lucky conjunction of the planets, on Thursday, which is the seventh day of the <foreign>pakṣa</foreign> and on which the <foreign>Nakṣatra</foreign> was <foreign>Uttiraṭṭāti</foreign> in the month of Tai, when the sun had gone into the Zodiac Capricorn, Matimāṉapañcara<note>"Who was an embodiment of wisdom and pride."</note> named Kulaṉtey, who is the Destroyer of the Pandyas, Vaṉuveri, the Atikāri of Laṅka, he whose shoulders are replete with decorations, the Teṉ, Parākramaṉ, Mēṇai the Commander of the forces, he who is the beloved of Tiru (Lakṣmī), built to flourish in Śrīpura nakara,<note>This place known as Malasnē, is situated near Hiripitaya in the Kuranāgala District. <title>J.R.A.S.</title> (C.B.) New Series Vol. IV (Sp. No.) p. 104.</note> a beautiful temple to the great Pōtimātavar (Bodhi Mātava), a monastery for monks, an alms hall for distribution of delicious food, a cayittam (<foreign>cetiya</foreign>), all this, and a college named Parākrama Atikāri Pirivuna.
                </p>
            </div>
            
